sat3: From Kelly's convo with her over the phone: Having more people for the input was nice. Very helpful, it gives you a lot of ideas and information. The book was helpful. Her partner got a CD with an audio-description of the book which was nice, she assumes this comes from the company that made the program (she's blind). The diversity of the class gives you a wider range of what works and the differences in what works for different people. They're not cookie-cutter one-size-fits-all, they think outside the box and try to find what works FOR YOU, which she finds much more helpful than previous nutritionists she's gone to in the past. The stuff she was taught was realistic and made it so she didn't have to "live like a rabbit" and could still do things she enjoys. Made huge improvements to her diabetes and her weight. The folks who run the class were really happy and willing to adapt things to her blindness, describe things and make her feel welcome. Made friendships. Can take it again to refresh. The classes are optimistic, "there are solutions to these problems, you just have to find the one that works for you, or that you can work with." Getting a handle on what she's eating and why she's eating it, realizing she can still have things she enjoys, just moderately.    Liked that it was online, because it was more accessible for her because she just needs someone to help her set it up, instead of take her to and from a physical location.
